Space Debris Tracker (C + DSA Project)
Overview

The Space Debris Tracker is a simulation-based system developed in C that monitors, analyzes, and manages space debris using multiple Data Structures and Algorithms (DSA) concepts.

It helps in:

Tracking debris objects
Calculating risk levels
Detecting possible collisions
Performing spatial searches
Simulating orbital movement
Key Concepts Used

This project integrates multiple DSA structures:

Linked List – Store all debris dynamically
Hash Table – Fast lookup using debris ID
Max Heap – Retrieve highest risk debris efficiently
KD-Tree – Spatial search (altitude and distance)
Circular Queue – Orbit simulation
Nested Traversal – Collision detection
Features
1. Add Debris
Input: ID, velocity, altitude, distance
Automatically computes risk factor
Inserts into all data structures
2. Display Debris
Shows all stored debris with:
Velocity
Altitude
Distance
Risk
3. Highest Risk Detection
Uses Max Heap
Retrieves debris with maximum risk instantly
4. Spatial Search (KD-Tree)
Search debris near:
Given altitude
Given distance
Efficient 2D searching
5. Orbit Simulation
Uses Circular Queue
Simulates debris movement step-by-step
6. Collision Detection
Compares debris pairs
Detects potential collision based on:
Distance difference < 500 km
Velocity difference < 0.5 km/s
Risk Calculation Formula

Risk is calculated using:

Risk = (velocity²) / (altitude × distance)

Higher value indicates more dangerous debris.

Project Structure
Debris Struct – Stores all debris attributes
KDNode Struct – Used for spatial indexing

Global Structures:

Linked List (head)
Hash Table
Max Heap
KD Tree Root
Circular Queue
How to Run
Compile

gcc debris_tracker.c -o debris

Execute

./debris

Menu Options
Add Debris
Display All Debris
Highest Risk Debris
Spatial Search
Orbit Simulation
Collision Detection
Exit
Example Workflow
Add multiple debris objects
View all entries
Check highest risk debris
Perform spatial search
Simulate orbit movement
Detect collisions
Real-World Relevance

This project simulates real-world space monitoring systems such as:

Satellite tracking
Space traffic management
Collision avoidance systems (used by ISRO/NASA)
